ocMA.OdeW1C12.text = "This phrase is from 1 Corinthians 2:6 and is therefore almost always used in connection with the Crucifixion. It is frequently inscribed on pectoral crosses and other depictions of the crucified Lord.

St Romanos speaks of human nature as ‘thorny’ in a number of his Kontakia. For example in On the Apostle Thomas (Strophe 2): ‘For from Thomas’s hand I believe in Moses’ story; For though it was perishable and thorny it was not consumed As it handled the side like a burning flame’. See also On the Nativity (Strophe 11). The idea very probably derives from St Ephrem the Syrian."

